# INTRODUCTION

The DAO Governance Handbook defines the operational rules, procedures, standards, and workflows that implement the DAO Constitution.  
It is the **primary reference manual** for:

- Ministers  
- Chapter leaders  
- Task force directors  
- Program operators  
- Registry stewards  
- Audit officers  
- Autonomous engines  

This handbook is binding on all DAO entities.

---

# PART I — GOVERNANCE STRUCTURE

## 1.1 Ring‑Based Authority Model
The DAO operates on a four‑ring authority system:

- **Ring 0** — Origin & Authorship  
- **Ring 1** — Foundational Governance  
- **Ring 2** — Ministries & Chapters  
- **Ring 3** — Programs, Task Forces, Local Entities  

Authority must always:

- Flow predictably  
- Respect ring boundaries  
- Be documented  
- Be lineage‑safe  

## 1.2 Governance Bodies
The DAO consists of:

- Foundational Council (Ring 1)  
- Ministries (Ring 2)  
- Chapters (Ring 2/3)  
- Task Forces (Ring 3)  
- Autonomous Engines (Special Classification)  

Each body must maintain:

- Identity anchors  
- Registry entries  
- Audit chains  
- Ethical compliance  
- Wellbeing compliance  

---

# PART II — IDENTITY & LINEAGE GOVERNANCE

## 2.1 Identity Anchors
Every governance actor must have:

- identity-anchor-record  
- lineage-binding  
- registry entry  
- audit chain linkage  

Identity anchors may not be altered without:

- Ethical validation  
- Audit entry  
- Registry update  

## 2.2 Lineage Governance
Lineage defines:

- Origin  
- Continuity  
- Succession  
- Stewardship  

All lineage actions must be:

- Immutable  
- Audit‑anchored  
- Succession‑safe  

---

# PART III — ETHICAL AUTHORITY

## 3.1 Ethical Invariants
All governance actions must:

- Preserve dignity  
- Reduce harm  
- Maintain transparency  
- Follow predictable rules  

## 3.2 Ethical Validation Workflow
Actions requiring validation include:

- Identity changes  
- Lineage changes  
- Authority delegation  
- Wellbeing decisions  
- Documentation overrides  

Validation steps:

1. Ethical review  
2. Harm‑reduction logic  
3. Documentation check  
4. Audit chain entry  

## 3.3 Ethical Flags
Governance actions may be flagged:

- dignity_sensitive  
- trauma_sensitive  
- non_punitive_only  
- requires_harm_reduction_review  
- requires_ethical_validation  

---

# PART IV — WELLBEING GOVERNANCE

## 4.1 Wellbeing as a Governance Requirement
All governance bodies must uphold:

- Stabilization  
- Assessment  
- Support planning  
- Continuity  
- Harm prevention  

## 4.2 Wellbeing Governance Standards
Governance decisions must follow:

- wellbeing.model.json  
- wellbeing.assessment.json  
- wellbeing.support-plan.json  
- wellbeing.stabilization.json  
- wellbeing.follow-up.json  

## 4.3 Prohibited Governance Actions
Governance may not:

- Punish  
- Coerce  
- Shame  
- Escalate harm  

---

# PART V — DOCUMENTATION & REGISTRY

## 5.1 Documentation Requirements
All governance records must be:

- Immutable  
- Version‑controlled  
- Registry‑anchored  
- Audit‑chained  

## 5.2 Registry Governance
The registry includes:

- Identity records  
- Lineage records  
- Badge records  
- Chapter records  
- Filing records  
- Audit chains  

Registry entries must:

- Follow schema  
- Include timestamps  
- Include chain IDs  

## 5.3 Documentation Integrity
No document may be:

- Deleted  
- Altered without versioning  
- Removed from the audit chain  

---

# PART VI — AUDIT GOVERNANCE

## 6.1 Audit Chain Requirements
Every governance event must include:

- Event ID  
- Timestamp  
- Actor ID  
- Hash  
- Previous hash  
- Context  
- Payload  

## 6.2 Chain Validation
Audit chains must be:

- Validated  
- Immutable  
- Linked  
- Complete  

## 6.3 Corrective Action
Corrective actions must be:

- Non‑punitive  
- Documented  
- Audit‑anchored  

---

# PART VII — OPERATIONAL GOVERNANCE

## 7.1 Standard Operating Procedures
All governance bodies must maintain SOPs for:

- Decision‑making  
- Documentation  
- Communication  
- Wellbeing actions  
- Emergency actions  
- Registry updates  
- Audit entries  

## 7.2 Emergency Governance
Emergency actions must:

- Preserve dignity  
- Avoid harm  
- Maintain continuity  
- Be logged immediately  

## 7.3 Delegated Authority
Delegation must:

- Be explicit  
- Be documented  
- Respect ring boundaries  
- Pass ethical validation  

---

# PART VIII — CHAPTER & MINISTRY GOVERNANCE

## 8.1 Ministry Governance
Ministries must:

- Maintain governance SOPs  
- Maintain registry entries  
- Maintain audit chains  
- Uphold wellbeing standards  

## 8.2 Chapter Governance
Chapters must:

- Follow chapter-charter-contract.md  
- Maintain community operations  
- Maintain documentation  
- Uphold ethical and wellbeing standards  

## 8.3 Task Force Governance
Task forces must:

- Operate within defined scope  
- Maintain logs  
- Maintain audit chains  

